First Dataset¶

The first dataset, TRAIN, contains annual information on the results of the La Via cooperative's campaigns, showing the following variables:

 CAMPAA: Year of the campaign.
 ID_FINCA: Farm identifier.
 ID_ZONA: Identifier of a zone with a common soil typology.
 ID_ESTACION: Identifier of meteorological station.
 ALTITUD: Average height of the farm above sea level in meters.
 VARIEDAD: Grape variety code of the grape grown on the estate.
 MODO: Code of the mode of cultivation.
 TIPO: Type of crop within the variety.
 COLOR: Grape color identifier.
 SUPERFICIE: Area in hectares occupied by the farm.
 PRODUCCION: Production in kg. Obtained in the campaign.

We can see that the variable heigth ("ALTITUD") is an object type which is not useful, so we will transform it with the following function that allows us to see if it is a single String value that we will replace it with the same value and if it is a range, we will separate the range in a list of two values and we will replace it with the average.

In [5]:
def formatoAltitud(row):
    if type(row['ALTITUD']) == str:
        range = [float(a) for a in row['ALTITUD'].split('-')]
        if len(range) > 2:
            return np.mean(range)
        else:
            return range[0]
    else:
        return row['ALTITUD']
    
TRAIN['ALTITUD'] = TRAIN.apply(formatoAltitud, axis=1)

Excluding the identifiers and campaign ("CAMPAA") we will see more information about the rest of the variables.

As expected, thanks to the correlation matrix, we can see that production is highly correlated with crop area.

Next, we visualize the distribution of all the variables and equally excluding the identifiers, with histplots to see the distribution of both continuous and categorical variables where we see that the binary variable MODE is more balanced than the binary variables TYPE and COLOR where a clear imbalance can be observed.

As for the variables VARIETY and ALTITUDE we can see that there are certain cases that are more common than the rest.

Finally, the variables PRODUCTION and SURFACE have a rather similar shape with a large asymmetry to the left.

We are going to start imputing the missing values of the variable "ALTITUD", for this we are going to go campaign by campaign imputing the missing values with the median of altitudes of the same station, in case we do not have the data of a station, that is to say, that station only has instances with the variable "ALTITUD" unknown, the median of the complete campaign will be used.

In [17]:
grupos = TRAIN.groupby('CAMPAA')

dataframes = {}
dataframes_ALTITUD = {}

for campaa, grupo in grupos:
    dataframes[campaa] = grupo.reset_index(level=0, drop=True)
    
for campaa, df in dataframes.items():
    df_ALTITUD = df.copy(deep = True)
    altitud = df_ALTITUD.groupby('ID_ESTACION').agg({'ALTITUD':np.nanmedian}).reset_index()
    for i, row in df_ALTITUD.iterrows():
        if pd.isna(row['ALTITUD']):
            alt = altitud[altitud['ID_ESTACION']==row['ID_ESTACION']]['ALTITUD'].values
            if np.isnan(alt[0]):
                df_ALTITUD.loc[i, 'ALTITUD'] = df_ALTITUD.agg({'ALTITUD':np.nanmedian}).values[0]
            else:
                df_ALTITUD.loc[i, 'ALTITUD'] = alt[0]
        else:
            pass
        dataframes_ALTITUD[campaa] = df_ALTITUD
        
TRAIN_ALTITUD = pd.concat(dataframes_ALTITUD.values(), ignore_index=True)

Now we are going to continue imputing the variable "SUPERFICIE", but we have the problem that for campaigns 14 to 19 we do not have any data, so we must commit data leakage and use information from the "future" to predict the "past".

For this we are going to use the information we have for the variable "SUPERFICIE" in our complete data set, taking into account the variables "VARIEDAD", "MODO", "TIPO", "COLOR" and "ID_FINCA".

    if pd.isna(row['SUPERFICIE']):
        
########################################################################################
#ALL VALUES ARE THE SAME (SAME ID_FINCA)
########################################################################################
        valores = list(data_superficie[(row['ID_FINCA'] == data_superficie['ID_FINCA']) & (row['VARIEDAD'] == data_superficie['VARIEDAD']) & (row['MODO'] == data_superficie['MODO']) & (row['TIPO'] == data_superficie['TIPO']) & (row['COLOR'] == data_superficie['COLOR'])]['SUPERFICIE'])
        if valores:
            if len(valores) > 1:
                TRAIN_SUPERFICIE.loc[i,'SUPERFICIE'] = np.mean(valores)

            else:
                TRAIN_SUPERFICIE.loc[i,'SUPERFICIE'] = valores[0]
                
########################################################################################
#ALL VALUES EXCEPT ONE ARE EQUAL (SAME ID_FINCA)
########################################################################################
        else:

Thanks to this imputation we can see that the missing values in "SUPERFICIE" have been considerably reduced.

For the remaining missing data of the variable "SURFACE" we are going to try different imputation methods to see which one suits us best.

  • Random imputation
  • Imputation of the mean
  • Imputation of the mode
  • Imputation of the median
  • Deterministic Regression Imputation
  • Stochastic Regression Imputation

Random imputation

In [22]:
grupos = TRAIN_SUPERFICIE.groupby('CAMPAA')

dataframes = {}
dataframes_final_rand = {}

for campaa, grupo in grupos:
    dataframes[campaa] = grupo.reset_index(level=0, drop=True)
    
for campaa, df in dataframes.items():
    datos_train_regresionR = df.copy(deep=True)

    number_missing = datos_train_regresionR['SUPERFICIE'].isnull().sum()
    observed_values = datos_train_regresionR.loc[datos_train_regresionR['SUPERFICIE'].notnull(), 'SUPERFICIE']
    datos_train_regresionR.loc[datos_train_regresionR['SUPERFICIE'].isnull(), 'SUPERFICIE'] = np.random.choice(observed_values, number_missing, replace = True)

    dataframes_final_rand[campaa] = datos_train_regresionR
        
TRAIN_FINAL_RAND = pd.concat(dataframes_final_rand.values(), ignore_index=True)
    
plt.figure(figsize=(8,4))
sns.histplot(x=TRAIN_FINAL_RAND['SUPERFICIE'], kde=True)
sns.histplot(x=TRAIN_SUPERFICIE['SUPERFICIE'], kde=True);

grupos = TRAIN_SUPERFICIE.groupby('CAMPAA')

for campaa, grupo in grupos:
    dataframes[campaa] = grupo.reset_index(level=0, drop=True)
    
for campaa, df in dataframes.items():

    datos_train_regresionD = df.copy(deep=True)
    columns = ['CAMPAA', 'ID_FINCA', 'ID_ZONA', 'ID_ESTACION', 'ALTITUD', 'VARIEDAD', 'MODO', 'TIPO', 'COLOR','SUPERFICIE']

    training_data = datos_train_regresionD[datos_train_regresionD['SUPERFICIE'].notnull()][columns]
    test_data = datos_train_regresionD[datos_train_regresionD['SUPERFICIE'].isnull()][columns]

    X_train = training_data.drop('SUPERFICIE', axis=1)
    y_train = training_data['SUPERFICIE']
    X_test = test_data.drop('SUPERFICIE', axis=1)

    model = LinearRegression()
    model.fit(X = X_train, y = y_train)

    predicted_values = model.predict(X_test)
    predicted_values = np.maximum(predicted_values, 0.00072)
    datos_train_regresionD.loc[datos_train_regresionD['SUPERFICIE'].isnull(), 'SUPERFICIE'] = predicted_values

    dataframes_final_regresionD[campaa] = datos_train_regresionD
        
TRAIN_FINAL_REGRESIOND = pd.concat(dataframes_final_regresionD.values(), ignore_index=True)
    
plt.figure(figsize=(8,4))

grupos = TRAIN_SUPERFICIE.groupby('CAMPAA')

dataframes = {}
dataframes_final_regresionS = {}

for campaa, grupo in grupos:
    dataframes[campaa] = grupo.reset_index(level=0, drop=True)
    
for campaa, df in dataframes.items():
    datos_train_regresionS = df.copy(deep=True)
    columns = ['CAMPAA', 'ID_FINCA', 'ID_ZONA', 'ID_ESTACION', 'ALTITUD', 'VARIEDAD', 'MODO', 'TIPO', 'COLOR','SUPERFICIE']

    training_data = datos_train_regresionS[datos_train_regresionS['SUPERFICIE'].notnull()][columns]
    test_data = datos_train_regresionS[datos_train_regresionS['SUPERFICIE'].isnull()][columns]

    X_train = training_data.drop('SUPERFICIE', axis=1)
    y_train = training_data['SUPERFICIE']
    X_test = test_data.drop('SUPERFICIE', axis=1)

    model = LinearRegression()
    model.fit(X = X_train, y = y_train)

    num_predictions = 10
    stochastic_predictions = np.empty((num_predictions, len(test_data)))
    for i in range(num_predictions):
        stochastic_predictions[i] = model.predict(X_test) + np.random.normal(0, 1, len(test_data))

    imputed_values = np.mean(stochastic_predictions, axis=0)
    imputed_values = np.maximum(imputed_values, 0.00072)

    datos_train_regresionS.loc[datos_train_regresionS['SUPERFICIE'].isnull(), 'SUPERFICIE'] = imputed_values
    dataframes_final_regresionS[campaa] = datos_train_regresionS
        
TRAIN_FINAL_REGRESIONS = pd.concat(dataframes_final_regresionS.values(), ignore_index=True)
    
plt.figure(figsize=(8,4))
sns.histplot(x=TRAIN_FINAL_REGRESIONS['SUPERFICIE'], kde=True)
sns.histplot(x=TRAIN_SUPERFICIE['SUPERFICIE'], kde=True);
